Balancing Summary (Double-AA Division):

The Double-AA division was balanced across 4 teams, each with an experienced head coach and supporting assistant coaches. Key balancing achievements:

  • All 4 teams have children paired with their volunteer parents
  • Team 1 (Clinch) focused on John Stanford Elementary students and Clinch-requested players
  • Team 2 (Wick) focused on McDonald International Elementary students and Louis Wick's requested teammates
  • Team 3 (Traube) focused on Daniel Bagley students and the Traube/Douglas family connections
  • Team 4 (Yokel) focused on St. Benedict/St. John students and the Yokel family's requested players
  • Major teammate request groupings were honored (Myles-Grayson-Jonah-Lachlan, Louis-Weston-Luca-Brendan-Cruz, Cameron-Jordan-Conor, and Oliver-Jude-Dylan-Chase)
  • School distribution is balanced with each team having a good mix of schools

Balancing Summary (Triple-AAA Division):

The Triple-AAA division was balanced across 4 teams with excellent volunteer coverage. Key balancing achievements include:

  • Team 1 (Bennett) focused on John Stanford Elementary students and Bennett's teammate network, with a core group of Finn-Quincy-Tove-Mateo-Riku-Yuiya
  • Team 2 (Hernandez) focused on West Woodland and BF Day Elementary students with the Hernandez-Butorac-Kruchoski connection and the BF Day group
  • Team 3 (Fox) primarily consists of St. John School students, honoring the St. John teammate requests
  • Team 4 (Lee) centered around Avery Lee's network from Greenwood Elementary and his teammate requests
  • All teams have parent-child connections and most coach requests were honored
  • School distribution is excellent with Team 1 focused on John Stanford, Team 2 on West Woodland/BF Day, Team 3 on St. John, and Team 4 on Greenwood
